> I know my thread is never doing anything with files, registry, etc so they can't become corrupted. Does that mean it's still safe? Also is that why it's considered unsafe?

It's never considered safe.  You never know exactly what that thread is doing at any given point in time and given that .NET runs on a VM it could be in the middle of an operation within the VM.  The [documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.thread.suspend?view=netframework-4.7.2) gives two examples of situations that could lead to deadlocks, but those are far from an exhaustive list.  The appropriate approach is to coordinate your threads using synchronization primitives, then you control exactly where they would block.

