@PathogenDavid commented on [Sat Apr 13 2019](https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/issues/2421#issuecomment-482826138)

(This sort-of turned into a ramble-rant. I hope you find it informative. I swear there's some insight for why using `Thread.Suspend` is a really bad idea buried in here. If you can't tell, I've been hurt by people who thought arbitrary thread suspension was a good idea. Thanks for helping me procrastinate on my taxes. 😁)

> Does that mean it's still safe?

If you have to ask: No, it is not. It is basically **never** safe to suspend sibling threads in your own process. (Sorry for being the "If you have to ask" guy. I hate that response too, but I think this really is a case where it applies.) It is always dangerous to suspend threads period. Hard stop. Do not pass go. Do not collect $200.

Suspending threads is almost always done for the wrong reasons. Here is when it's OK to suspend threads arbitrarily:

* You are writing the task schedule for an operating system.
* You are writing an out of process debugger.
* You have a lot of control over the execution environment and you know enough about what you're doing to write [many paragraphs](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/cb22707acb620e93a30254ded3048912a9ccb26f/src/vm/threads.h#L36-L132) about why it's OK in your context, why you need it, and how you do it. (Side note: [threadsuspend.cpp](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/0fed62e68d1f8f8a756ec8ba5348bfde61057666/src/vm/threadsuspend.cpp) is 7,199 lines long. Pretty spoopy.)

This list is exhaustive.

"I think I have a legitimate use case." You probably don't.

"I wrote a task scheduler for an embedded OS, I know what I'm talking about. I'm making a simulator for that OS that runs on Windows. I'm just adapting that same logic for thread scheduling of OS threads to Windows threads." You're looking at this from an embedded point of view, that won't work how you want it to.

"Hey David, remember when we ignored you a while back. Fun times. Anyway, the simulator locks up constantly, especially the ones that have graphics. Can you fix it?" 🙃

(In the unlikely event a former coworker finds this: I know I simplified and dramatized a bit there 😬)

--------------------

> Also is that why it's considered unsafe?

To demonstrate why suspending an arbitrary thread is unsafe, let's consider the following two threads:

```csharp
while (true)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Hello, world!");
}
```

Is it safe to suspend this thread at an arbitrary time?

If you thought: "Of course! It's hello world, the simplest of all programs." You would unfortunately be incorrect.

To understand why, we have to consider how `Console.WriteLine` is implemented. (This also applies to `printf` and the underlying OS functionality for writing to consoles that it uses. This whole thing is a computing issue, not a C# one.)

Imagine `Console.WriteLine` looks like this pseudocode down at the lower levels:

```c
void ConsoleWriteLineInternals(const char* message)
{
    AcquireConsoleBufferLock();
    CopyToConsoleBuffer(message);
    ReleaseConsoleBufferLock();
}
```

That console buffer lock is used to ensure that if multiple threads write to the console at once, no output is lost. Normally this lock is held for a very short period of time - only as long as it takes to copy the message to the console buffer.

Now imagine we suspend this thread while this lock is held. If another thread comes along and tries to write the console, that thread will have to wait for the lock to be released. Unfortunately it might never be released because the thread which owns the lock is suspended, so the operating system will never schedule it for execution.

--------------------

Here are full examples in both C# and C++ if you want to run it for yourself to see it lock up: https://github.com/PathogenPlayground/ThreadSuspendIsBad

If you break and look at the main thread in the debugger during the deadlock, the C# one will be stuck in `SyncTextWriter.WriteLine` since the framework has an internal lock for the console.  In the C++ one you'll see it's stuck trying to acquire a lock with [`RtlEnterCriticalSection`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-entercriticalsection). (Note: You need to load symbols for `ntdll.dll` to see that for the C++ version. Right-click the stack frame and load symbols in Visual Studio.)

--------------------

If you have more questions or want clarification, feel free to ask. I was a little all over the place there, so it wouldn't surprise me if I left something out and made it confusing as a result.

BTW, `Thread.Suspend` isn't actually implemented in .NET Core.

